english:
  title: Afterword to the Collected Works of Geunsa Hall
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the Yuan court, scholars from the northern frontier rose to prominence through their mastery of classical prose. Among them—Ma Zuchangyongyu Que, and Tingxin—several stood remarkably apart. In the year of Eulyu, Byeok-yo Sun Gongyuan, who had passed the examination, studied in the south. Before reaching twenty, he had mastered the prescribed texts, and in his spare hours devoted himself to classical prose, earning great renown. Upon receiving his degree, he served in the Hanlin Academy and was appointed Keeper of the Characters in the Hall of Establishing Roots. Later he was promoted to Director of the Imperial Library of Reverence, and seemed destined for high office. Yet those in power harbored grievance against his father, the Left Minister of Huainan. Thus Gongyuan was sent to govern Shanzhou, where he earned repute as an able administrator.

    Soon after, he mourned his mother and dwelt in Daning. By then the rebels had breached the Upper Capital and turned toward the Liaodong frontier. Gongyuan gathered his children, mounted a single horse, crossed the Liao waters, and entered Goryeo. Days later, the rebel forces descended upon Daning itself.

    The king, remembering Gongyuan's service in his household, welcomed him with honors. Upon their meeting, he was treated with exceptional courtesy—granted estates in Fuyuan and enfeoffed as Lord of the Three Excellencies. There Gongyuan dwelt several years before succumbing to illness.

    His brothers Gongwen and Gongsso, grieving the scattering of his literary remains, collected his verses of note into two volumes. Yet when the year Sinchuk brought upheaval, these too were lost. It was only through fortune that Gold Commissioner Jin Ziyun discovered one volume amid the ashes and restored it to the Byeok family—that great Uyghur clan, which entered the Middle Kingdom as an illustrious house. Nine of their descendants passed the examinations. For generations they transmitted the teachings of poetry, ritual, and righteousness, and Gongyuan gathered the brilliance of his line and let it shine forth. His writings gleam with clarity, standing equal to those of Baiyong and Tingxin, and surely will be transmitted to posterity. Yet even before his death, these works were lost—lost once, and lost again, until scarcely anything remained. How tragic this is!

    Now these manuscripts before us are the works of his youth, yet they carry the austere polish of age. What he achieved in his prime, we can only imagine.

    His son Cheonwoo, official of the Bureau of Merit, asked me: "That this manuscript survives is due to Magistrate Kim's efforts. My elder brother Cheonmin is honored to preserve it, and we shall have it carved into blocks for safekeeping in our provincial academy. I humbly request your preface." Thus I have briefly chronicled Gongyuan's life and circumstances, and recorded how this precious volume came to be preserved, that future compilers of literary collections might have this account as their witness.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Hall of Establishing Roots' (Danbengtang) was an educational institution in the Yuan court.
    - The year of Eulyu (乙酉) marks the establishment of the examination system mentioned. Sinchuk (辛丑) refers to a year of warfare and turmoil during the Yuan's fall.
    - The Byeok (偰) family were descendants of Uyghurs who integrated into Chinese society and rose to prominence through scholarly achievement.
    - Lee Saek was himself a renowned scholar and official of Goryeo who preserved much literary and historical knowledge during the Yuan period.
